# UI and Styling

## Use MUI Theme and Tokens

Pull visual values from **MUI's theme** — palette, spacing, typography, breakpoints, shape — instead of hardcoding hex colors or magic pixel values.

```tsx
// ❌ BAD
<Box sx={{ color: '#3a86ff', p: '13px' }} />

// ✅ GOOD
<Box sx={{ color: 'primary.main', p: 2 }} />
```

Use `useTheme()` when you need theme values in logic (e.g. media queries with `theme.breakpoints`).

## Prefer `sx` and MUI Primitives

Use MUI layout and input primitives (`Box`, `Stack`, `Typography`, `Paper`, etc.) and the **`sx` prop** for one-off layout and responsive rules. Use **`styled`** from `@mui/material/styles` when a style variant is reused across multiple instances.

## No Inline Styles Except Truly Dynamic Values

Avoid raw `style={{}}` on DOM elements. Exceptions: values that must be computed at runtime and cannot be expressed with theme tokens or `sx` (e.g. dynamic height from measurements).

## Do Not Introduce Another CSS Framework

This project uses **MUI + Emotion**. Do not add Tailwind, styled-components, or CSS-in-JS libraries alongside MUI without an explicit decision to migrate.

## Markdown and User Content

Rich message rendering lives in components like `MarkdownMessage` with **sanitize** pipeline (`rehype-sanitize`). When changing markdown or HTML rendering, preserve sanitization and accessibility (headings, links, contrast).
